Tanking in the NBA

Rohan Dixit & Glenn Ren

CMSC 320

1. Introduction

Over recent years, many sports teams have completely revamped their management strategy. They have begun to rely more on analytics and less on qualitative “expert” opinions. In baseball, the Oakland A’s famously used this to their advantage when they built a competitive team out of underutilized players. However, this strategy is less effective in sports such as basketball due to its star-driven nature. Talent reigns supreme and the success of a team is tied closely to the success of their superstar player(s).

Thus, NBA teams looking to get better have two options - draft and develop a player out of college or sign a current superstar during free agency. Unfortunately for most, the latter option is not feasible. Superstars want to win with other superstars in large markets which leaves the losing teams in smaller markets with only the draft.

What is tanking?

“The point of the draft is to restock the worst-performing teams. They’re just not supposed to be worst-performing by design.”

- NBA Commissioner Adam Silver

Tanking occurs when teams that are not going to make the playoffs intentionally start trying to lose so that they have a higher probability of getting better draft picks. In the NBA, teams with the worst record have the highest likelihood of receiving the first draft pick, which means they would be able to draft the best players from college. This would help a team in the rebuilding phase. A summary of the NBA Draft Lottery can be found here: https://www.nba.com/nba-draft-lottery-explainer

The NBA has been attempting to curb tanking by changing rules that may provide benefit to lower performing teams. Typically, teams with lower records earn a higher draft pick. Therefore, the NBA instituted a lottery based system that does not make it deterministic that the lowest standing team in the NBA receives the first (best) pick in the NBA draft: https://www.si.com/nba/2019/05/15/nba-draft-lottery-lebron-james-anthony-davis-lakers-pelicans-tanking-not-dead

In order to tank and lose, teams sometimes choose to trade away their good players, play their younger/worse players more often to get them more experience. In recent years, teams have openly acknowledged tanking, such as the Dallas Mavericks in 2018 (https://twitter.com/ESPNNBA/status/965979545856806914). This past year tanking has been an even bigger point of discussion as several teams, most notably the New York Knicks, have been losing with the goal of getting the first pick and the top player in the draft, Zion Williamson: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zouIqKN8rZA.

Project Motivation

Because tanking has become such a common point of discussion over the past year, we thought it would be interesting to attempt to quantify tanking in the NBA to determine if teams were making a deliberate attempt to lose. This information would be especially important to know for the NBA to decide whether or not they should change rules or fine teams for tanking during the season. We decided to use not this season’s but the previous season (2017-2018) data since the current season is ongoing and the previous year’s data is more complete.

In order to do so, we decided to look at primarily two variables: how strong was a team’s lineup and their winning percentage throughout the season. We hypothesize that teams with a low winning percentage will have a declining strength in their team lineup as they try to tank.

Although winning percentage can easily be calculated based on a team’s win and loss record, we had to design a metric to quantify how good a team’s lineup was. This also meant we needed to have a way to quantify how good players in a lineup were. The folllowing tutorial will explain our data processing to make these calculations and overall measure the relationship between win percentage and strength of lineup.

Player Ratings

To measure overall player rating, we decided to use the video game NBA 2K18’s player ratings. NBA 2K18 is highly respected for the ratings that it reveals each year with players obsessed about how the game judges their gameplay.

We downloaded ratings for every player in the game from this link: https://www.dropbox.com/s/js2hqcd152mq4kh/NBA%202k18%20All%20Players%20Master.xls?dl=0. This document also contains player ratings for historical teams so to focus our analysis on this year, we filtered by year 2017/2018.

One limitation of this document is that it does not contain free agents’ ratings who do not begin on a team but can be signed by a team. We will explain how we dealt with this in a later section.

Player Weighting

We decided to multiply a player’s rating by the number of minutes that they played in a game to determine how much they contribute in value to a team. Then for each team’s game on a given date, we summed up each players weighted rating to determine the overall team rating for that game.

teamstrength <- merged %>%
  mutate(WeightedRating = Minutes*Rating, DateFormat=as.Date(Date, "%m/%d/%Y")) %>%
  group_by(DateFormat, Team) %>%
  summarize(GameTeamStrength=sum(WeightedRating))

Overview

There were some limitations of these graphs. For some teams, it was not a deliberate attempt to lose but sometimes their star players got injured causing the curve to decline. For example, the Washington Wizards declined because of the injury to John Wall, the New York Knicks lost Kristaps Porzingis, and the Memphis Grizzlies lost Mike Conley.

Sometimes the graphs went upwards unexpectedly because of trades midseason or free agent signings. Dwyane Wade was signed by the Miami Heat, the Pistons received Blake Griffin (trade) which caused their team strength value to increase.

However, by analyzing individual box scores from midseason to the end of the season, we can see that some other players may have gotten more minutes.

EDA for Winning Percentage & Streaks

Winning Streaks

# INPUT:  3 character abbreviation of team name
# OUTPUT: vector of length 82

getTeamStrk <- function(teamName) {
  # Pipeline to get game date, team abbreviation, opponent abbreviation and game result attributes
  teamResults <- allBoxScores %>%
    filter(teamAbbr == teamName) %>%
    mutate(strkChange = ifelse(teamRslt == "Win", 1, -1)) %>%
    mutate(gameNum = 1:82)
  
  # Store run length encoding information for team wins/losses
  # Length of streak (1, 2, 3, ...)
  strkLengths <- rle(teamResults$strkChange)$lengths
  # Type of streak (-1 for loss /1 for win)
  strkTypes <- rle(teamResults$strkChange)$values
  # Expand vector of streaks into list of vectors
  # c(3, 2, 4) -> [c(1,2,3), c(1,2), c(1,2,3,4)]
  strkRuns <- sapply(strkLengths, function(i) seq(1, i))
  # Multiply each streak by its type
  strkSeason <- Map('*', strkRuns, strkTypes)
  # Collapse list of vectors into single vector
  strkSeason <- unlist(strkSeason)
  
  teamResults$currStrk = strkSeason
  
  return (teamResults)
}
teams <- allBoxScores %>%
  select(teamAbbr)
# Remove duplicate teams
teams <- unique(teams)
# Sort tibble alphabetically by teamAbbr
teams <- sort(teams$teamAbbr)

allStreaksList <- bind_rows(invisible(lapply(teams, getTeamStrk)))

Combining Everything into One Dataframe

names(teamstrength)[names(teamstrength) == 'DateFormat'] <- 'gmDate'
names(teamstrength)[names(teamstrength) == 'Team'] <- 'teamAbbr'
# Join "Game Strength" data frame with "Streaks" data frame
master_df <- merge(allStreaksList, teamstrength, by = c("gmDate", "teamAbbr"))

master_df <- master_df %>%
  mutate(won = ifelse(strkChange == 1, 1, 0))

master_df$currWins <- ave(master_df$won, master_df$teamAbbr, FUN = cumsum)

library(plyr)

master_df <- master_df %>%
  mutate(winningPer = currWins / gameNum) %>%
  mutate(meanStrength=mean(GameTeamStrength), stStrength=sd(GameTeamStrength), standardizedStrength = (GameTeamStrength - meanStrength)/stStrength)
master_df <- ddply(master_df, c("teamAbbr"), transform, winningPer.std = scale(winningPer))

Clustering Teams

For the last part of this tutorial, we’ll try to cluster teams based on the main two attributes that we identified in the beginning - team strength and winning percentage.

We wanted a detailed look into

Tanking has become such a common issue among the league’s worst performing teams. For further analysis, we plan on looking at past seasons and checking if the number of teams in the bottom left quadrant has increased.

library(class)
library(broom)

midseason_df <- master_df %>%
  filter(gameNum <= 41)
midseason_df$avgStrength <- ave(midseason_df$GameTeamStrength, midseason_df$teamAbbr)

end_df <- master_df %>%
  filter(41 < gameNum)
